    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-07T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-07T07:00:00-05:00" n="41"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d41">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72119/8594: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wallace</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-07T12:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 7, 1920, noon.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received 5.32 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mission 57. Your 3906, November 27, 2 p.m.,<note n="21" xml:id="d41fn21">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_21">p. 21</ref>.</note> to the
                    Mission, next to last paragraph. I should appreciate receiving instructions
                    concerning my part in the meeting of the so-called Committee of Ambassadors.
                    This will probably take place early in coming week since treaty may become
                    effective next Saturday. I may point out in regard to this matter that my
                    attendance unofficially upon these committee meetings from the very first would
                    be of advantage should the United States ratify the treaty at an early date.
                    Objection by my colleagues seems unlikely.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wallace</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
